<v Announcer>We're gonna turn our attention back</v>

3
00:00:10.140 --> 00:00:11.793
to behavioral medicine,

4
00:00:13.380 --> 00:00:15.330
but Dr. Heinrich, of course, is back,

5
00:00:15.330 --> 00:00:18.180
and he's gonna take it over for behavioral medicine II.

6
00:00:18.180 --> 00:00:19.013
Thank you, sir.

7
00:00:19.013 --> 00:00:21.060
<v ->All right, so we'll talk about bipolar disorder</v>

8
00:00:21.060 --> 00:00:23.430
and anxiety disorders here.

9
00:00:23.430 --> 00:00:26.550
Nothing to disclose on these topics either.

10
00:00:26.550 --> 00:00:29.280
What we're gonna talk is about the differential diagnosis

11
00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:30.987
and clinical presentation of bipolar disorder

12
00:00:30.987 --> 00:00:33.360
and anxiety disorders, and surprise, surprise,

13
00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:34.193
we're gonna follow that

14
00:00:34.193 --> 00:00:36.600
by talking about some treatment recommendations

15
00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:38.160
for them from a pharmacotherapy

16
00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:40.710
and a non-pharmcotherapy standpoint.

17
00:00:40.710 --> 00:00:42.720
Again, I have Dr. Oakley to thank,

18
00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:45.630
Stan, for the basis of these slides,

19
00:00:45.630 --> 00:00:46.833
which I've built on.

20
00:00:47.970 --> 00:00:50.583
So let's start with AES.

21
00:00:51.870 --> 00:00:55.110
Which is of the following true about bipolar disorder:

22
00:00:55.110 --> 00:00:58.530
kindling is the acceleration of untreated mood swings;

23
00:00:58.530 --> 00:01:02.460
bipolar disorder occurs more commonly in men than women;

24
00:01:02.460 --> 00:01:07.193
bipolar II is characterized by depression, along with mania;

25
00:01:08.070 --> 00:01:10.500
and patients with bipolar II may both have manic

26
00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:14.103
and hypomanic episodes, along with their depression?

27
00:01:19.020 --> 00:01:22.443
Ooh, I did this one good. All right.

28
00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:27.330
All right, so we have a little mix between A and B,

29
00:01:27.330 --> 00:01:30.300
and we'll kind of go through the talk and answer that here.

30
00:01:30.300 --> 00:01:34.230
Nice, I find when talking about bipolar disorder,

31
00:01:34.230 --> 00:01:36.900
it's best to define different mood states

32
00:01:36.900 --> 00:01:39.570
because they're very relevant to the diagnosis of bipolar.

33
00:01:39.570 --> 00:01:41.760
So we're gonna talk about what mania is.

34
00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:43.830
We're gonna talk about what hypomania is,

35
00:01:43.830 --> 00:01:44.820
what it looks like.

36
00:01:44.820 --> 00:01:46.620
We've already talked a little bit about depression,

37
00:01:46.620 --> 00:01:49.380
and then we're gonna talk about mixed mood states.

38
00:01:49.380 --> 00:01:51.750
So what is mania?

39
00:01:51.750 --> 00:01:54.720
Mania requires that the patient either has an irritable

40
00:01:54.720 --> 00:01:55.920
or euphoric mood,

41
00:01:55.920 --> 00:01:59.970
along with increased goal-directed activity or energy.

42
00:01:59.970 --> 00:02:04.410
So they can be irritable, irritable manics are not pleasant.

43
00:02:04.410 --> 00:02:06.690
Grandiose manics can be a little bit more fun

44
00:02:06.690 --> 00:02:08.160
when you're talking to them,

45
00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:12.090
but they have these cardinal symptoms of mania,

46
00:02:12.090 --> 00:02:16.290
and if it's manic grandiosity, they need three symptoms,

47
00:02:16.290 --> 00:02:17.550
but if it's an irritable type,

48
00:02:17.550 --> 00:02:19.500
they need four of these cardinal symptoms,

49
00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:22.290
and I'll talk about those in my next slides.

50
00:02:22.290 --> 00:02:25.140
For mania, they have to have these symptoms present

51
00:02:25.140 --> 00:02:26.070
for at least a week,

52
00:02:26.070 --> 00:02:30.060
unless they get psychiatrically hospitalized before that,

53
00:02:30.060 --> 00:02:31.620
that counts, okay?

54
00:02:31.620 --> 00:02:36.300
And these patients have significant social,

55
00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:39.660
educational, employment dysfunction associated

56
00:02:39.660 --> 00:02:42.360
with this mania episode.

57
00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:44.340
These are those cardinal symptoms.

58
00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:45.870
The mnemonic is DIG FAST.

59
00:02:45.870 --> 00:02:48.510
They're very distractable, they're quite impulsive

60
00:02:48.510 --> 00:02:50.760
with rapid traveling and spending,

61
00:02:50.760 --> 00:02:52.320
they can be very grandiose

62
00:02:52.320 --> 00:02:55.230
with thoughts about being the next coming of Jesus,

63
00:02:55.230 --> 00:02:57.150
or inventing the next great

64
00:02:57.150 --> 00:02:59.550
Nobel Prize winning physics advancement,

65
00:02:59.550 --> 00:03:01.590
they can have flight of ideas in which they jump

66
00:03:01.590 --> 00:03:04.170
from topic to topic during the conversation,

67
00:03:04.170 --> 00:03:07.200
and you're left mouth agape kind of difficulty,

68
00:03:07.200 --> 00:03:08.730
kind of wondering what's going on.

69
00:03:08.730 --> 00:03:10.950
They can have a lot of goal-directed activities.

70
00:03:10.950 --> 00:03:13.710
They're writing the next great play,

71
00:03:13.710 --> 00:03:15.000
at the same time a novel,

72
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:16.890
at the same time they're working three jobs,

73
00:03:16.890 --> 00:03:18.780
and cleaning and raising children.

74
00:03:18.780 --> 00:03:21.360
Not well necessarily, but trying.

75
00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:22.320
They're not sleeping.

76
00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:24.300
And unlike depressed patients who aren't sleeping,

77
00:03:24.300 --> 00:03:25.410
they're not tired.

78
00:03:25.410 --> 00:03:27.723
They don't need to sleep, okay?

79
00:03:28.590 --> 00:03:29.730
And they're very talkative,

80
00:03:29.730 --> 00:03:32.340
much like me trying to fit all of this into 30 minutes.

81
00:03:32.340 --> 00:03:35.100
All right, how does that differentiate

82
00:03:35.100 --> 00:03:37.200
from a hypomanic episode?

83
00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:40.050
Well, it differs in level of severity.

84
00:03:40.050 --> 00:03:42.300
They still need those criteria.

85
00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:45.824
A grandiose hypomanic still needs three

86
00:03:45.824 --> 00:03:47.070
of those cardinal symptoms,

87
00:03:47.070 --> 00:03:50.610
and an irritable still needs four, but it's not,

88
00:03:50.610 --> 00:03:53.670
they don't have the significant level of impairment.

89
00:03:53.670 --> 00:03:55.350
They're able to maintain a job.

90
00:03:55.350 --> 00:03:58.110
They may get warnings, but they're able,

91
00:03:58.110 --> 00:03:59.490
they're not like escorted out

92
00:03:59.490 --> 00:04:02.430
when they come in completely manic, okay?

93
00:04:02.430 --> 00:04:03.840
And fired on the spot.

94
00:04:03.840 --> 00:04:07.380
So there is impairment, but not significant impairment.

95
00:04:07.380 --> 00:04:09.570
The episode duration is shorter.

96
00:04:09.570 --> 00:04:10.950
They can be only four days.

97
00:04:10.950 --> 00:04:13.410
They don't need that entire week,

98
00:04:13.410 --> 00:04:15.120
but it's still a change in behavior

99
00:04:15.120 --> 00:04:17.520
that's observable by others.

100
00:04:17.520 --> 00:04:19.800
These patients do not get psychotic,

101
00:04:19.800 --> 00:04:24.600
and if they get psychotic, they bump up to mania.

102
00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:27.360
Depression, the depressed mood state we just talked about,

103
00:04:27.360 --> 00:04:28.410
in bipolar disorder,

104
00:04:28.410 --> 00:04:30.870
it's the same criteria we use for major depression.

105
00:04:30.870 --> 00:04:33.750
You don't have to memorize new things or anything like that.

106
00:04:33.750 --> 00:04:37.200
However, if somebody has a depressive,

107
00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:39.750
meets those criteria and has a history of hypomania

108
00:04:39.750 --> 00:04:43.410
or mania, they bounce into bipolar category.

109
00:04:43.410 --> 00:04:45.930
No longer major depressive disorder.

110
00:04:45.930 --> 00:04:50.370
Now, mixed episodes are terrible episodes for patients.

111
00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:54.270
They are both irritable, and grandiose,

112
00:04:54.270 --> 00:04:55.770
and depressed at the same time.

113
00:04:55.770 --> 00:04:58.650
They meet criteria for both a manic episode,

114
00:04:58.650 --> 00:05:01.560
and both a depressed episode at the same time.

115
00:05:01.560 --> 00:05:04.020
Can you imagine being clinically depressed,

116
00:05:04.020 --> 00:05:05.940
but having all the energy in the world

117
00:05:05.940 --> 00:05:07.980
and not feeling like you need to sleep?

118
00:05:07.980 --> 00:05:11.370
That's gotta be terrible, and it is terrible.

119
00:05:11.370 --> 00:05:13.110
It's associated with a higher risk of suicide

120
00:05:13.110 --> 00:05:15.030
than other bipolar mood states.

121
00:05:15.030 --> 00:05:18.480
So not a pleasant experience.

122
00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:20.790
So with that understanding of the mood states,

123
00:05:20.790 --> 00:05:23.670
we can switch to talk actually about the diagnostic criteria

124
00:05:23.670 --> 00:05:26.073
of bipolar I and bipolar II.

125
00:05:27.240 --> 00:05:30.270
So if you have a history of a manic episode,

126
00:05:30.270 --> 00:05:32.070
you have bipolar I.

127
00:05:32.070 --> 00:05:34.020
Not very hard, okay?

128
00:05:34.020 --> 00:05:35.070
That's the diagnosis.

129
00:05:35.070 --> 00:05:38.703
If you've had a manic episode, you have bipolar I.

130
00:05:39.870 --> 00:05:42.390
It can't be explained by hyperthyroidism

131
00:05:42.390 --> 00:05:45.480
or something else, but you have bipolar I.

132
00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:46.710
This is kind of what it looks like.

133
00:05:46.710 --> 00:05:48.990
You have the manic episodes that reach that red line,

134
00:05:48.990 --> 00:05:50.430
and you have the depressive episodes,

135
00:05:50.430 --> 00:05:52.320
but you actually don't need a depressive episode

136
00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:53.973
to get a diagnosis of bipolar I.

137
00:05:54.930 --> 00:05:57.870
We'll see that a vast, vast, vast majority do,

138
00:05:57.870 --> 00:05:59.310
but you don't necessarily need it.

139
00:05:59.310 --> 00:06:00.540
I don't think I've ever seen anybody

140
00:06:00.540 --> 00:06:02.400
who hasn't had a major depressive episode,

141
00:06:02.400 --> 00:06:05.700
but you theoretically could.

142
00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:08.100
So they kind of cycle between this manic and depressive,

143
00:06:08.100 --> 00:06:10.800
hence the old name of manic depressive illness.

144
00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:14.130
It's a very chronic disease, unfortunately, and reoccurring,

145
00:06:14.130 --> 00:06:16.830
and this is where the concept of kindling comes in.

146
00:06:16.830 --> 00:06:18.120
The concept of kindling is

147
00:06:18.120 --> 00:06:21.540
if they have more untreated mood episodes,

148
00:06:21.540 --> 00:06:24.810
the likelihood of the next one comes on quicker,

149
00:06:24.810 --> 00:06:27.210
is more severe and more difficult to treat.

150
00:06:27.210 --> 00:06:28.920
The brain just gets kind of used to that,

151
00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:31.410
so it kindles and the episodes become more frequent

152
00:06:31.410 --> 00:06:32.580
and more severe.

153
00:06:32.580 --> 00:06:36.510
Really stresses the importance of diagnosing

154
00:06:36.510 --> 00:06:38.583
and treating as quickly as possible.

155
00:06:39.540 --> 00:06:42.390
The average length of depression is a little longer

156
00:06:42.390 --> 00:06:44.760
than in major depression, with about six to 12 months,

157
00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:47.250
whereas mania is a little shorter, up to three months.

158
00:06:47.250 --> 00:06:50.250
That's if you don't do anything and just kind of watch this.

159
00:06:51.480 --> 00:06:53.370
It's got actually a fairly low prevalence.

160
00:06:53.370 --> 00:06:55.650
This prevalence has been increasing

161
00:06:55.650 --> 00:06:57.840
as the diagnostic criteria tends to get

162
00:06:57.840 --> 00:07:00.150
a little bit more sophisticated.

163
00:07:00.150 --> 00:07:02.190
It's less than 1%, with an equal rate

164
00:07:02.190 --> 00:07:04.770
between male and female of one to one.

165
00:07:04.770 --> 00:07:07.710
The mean age of onset is about 18 years of age,

166
00:07:07.710 --> 00:07:10.830
so right around early adulthood,

167
00:07:10.830 --> 00:07:13.320
but it does occur throughout the life span.

168
00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:15.450
I will tell you that if I'm seeing somebody

169
00:07:15.450 --> 00:07:19.830
at age 55 or 60 that has no history of mania or depression

170
00:07:19.830 --> 00:07:21.840
and is coming across as manic,

171
00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:25.020
they're getting maybe not quite a million-dollar workup

172
00:07:25.020 --> 00:07:28.350
for other causes, but I'm getting a call from somebody

173
00:07:28.350 --> 00:07:30.063
about how expensive my workup is.

174
00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:33.420
I alluded to the fact that I've really never seen somebody

175
00:07:33.420 --> 00:07:34.740
with just a manic episode.

176
00:07:34.740 --> 00:07:37.350
They often will have another manic episode or a depressive.

177
00:07:37.350 --> 00:07:40.200
That's because 90% of patients after a manic episode

178
00:07:40.200 --> 00:07:42.240
will go on to develop another mood state,

179
00:07:42.240 --> 00:07:44.940
major depressive and mania.

180
00:07:44.940 --> 00:07:48.840
Bipolar II, they cannot have any history

181
00:07:48.840 --> 00:07:51.060
of a manic episode, okay?

182
00:07:51.060 --> 00:07:54.060
They can only have that hypomanic episode,

183
00:07:54.060 --> 00:07:58.020
and they do need a past episode of major depression

184
00:07:58.020 --> 00:08:01.110
to have that diagnosis, or, at some point,

185
00:08:01.110 --> 00:08:02.730
they'll have that diagnosis.

186
00:08:02.730 --> 00:08:05.730
The rate is a little bit more than bipolar I, at 0.8.

187
00:08:05.730 --> 00:08:07.913
So between the two, you're at about 1.4, 1.5.

188
00:08:09.180 --> 00:08:11.880
And the clinical data really does suggest,

189
00:08:11.880 --> 00:08:15.123
unlike bipolar I, it's more prevalent in women than in men.

190
00:08:16.530 --> 00:08:18.390
Usually begins with a depressive course.

191
00:08:18.390 --> 00:08:23.160
About 70% of them start with depression,

192
00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:25.020
and then they go on to, in the future,

193
00:08:25.020 --> 00:08:27.000
develop that kind of hypomania.

194
00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:29.190
The number of episodes, the different mood states

195
00:08:29.190 --> 00:08:32.790
between depression and hypomania are more than in bipolar I,

196
00:08:32.790 --> 00:08:34.980
so there's a more frequent switch,

197
00:08:34.980 --> 00:08:37.440
but the really good news is there isn't this progression

198
00:08:37.440 --> 00:08:38.610
to bipolar I.

199
00:08:38.610 --> 00:08:41.730
Patients with bipolar II tend to stay at bipolar II,

200
00:08:41.730 --> 00:08:45.840
with only 10, 15% progressing onto bipolar I,

201
00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:48.033
so that's actually pretty good news.

202
00:08:48.900 --> 00:08:50.010
And this is what it looks like.

203
00:08:50.010 --> 00:08:52.020
They never get up to that high manic state,

204
00:08:52.020 --> 00:08:55.170
but they do hit the depressive state, okay?

205
00:08:55.170 --> 00:08:56.013
Red and blue.

206
00:08:57.150 --> 00:09:02.070
Now, cyclothymia, I have never diagnosed it,

207
00:09:02.070 --> 00:09:04.320
I have never seen it diagnosed,

208
00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:06.843
but I have seen it on a board question,

209
00:09:08.040 --> 00:09:10.050
not as the primary, but as a confounder,

210
00:09:10.050 --> 00:09:12.270
so it's included here.

211
00:09:12.270 --> 00:09:14.310
So kind of like that persistent depressive,

212
00:09:14.310 --> 00:09:16.290
this is a prolonged mood state.

213
00:09:16.290 --> 00:09:20.430
For over two years, there's been symptoms of hypomania,

214
00:09:20.430 --> 00:09:22.680
but never meeting the criteria of hypomania,

215
00:09:22.680 --> 00:09:26.820
and symptoms of depression, but never meeting the criteria

216
00:09:26.820 --> 00:09:29.280
for major depression for two years.

217
00:09:29.280 --> 00:09:31.320
The real key aspect is you're getting a history

218
00:09:31.320 --> 00:09:33.030
that they've never clicked all the boxes

219
00:09:33.030 --> 00:09:36.930
for hypomania, mania or depression to actually get this,

220
00:09:36.930 --> 00:09:39.240
but still have this kind of cycling

221
00:09:39.240 --> 00:09:42.180
around this midline of euthymic state.

222
00:09:42.180 --> 00:09:44.643
Again, I don't know. I've never seen it.

223
00:09:46.200 --> 00:09:49.950
As we're continuing this trend as depression as a symptom

224
00:09:49.950 --> 00:09:51.720
that requires a differential diagnosis,

225
00:09:51.720 --> 00:09:53.010
the same as for mania.

226
00:09:53.010 --> 00:09:55.200
I mentioned bipolar disorder can occur

227
00:09:55.200 --> 00:09:57.690
throughout the lifespan, but if I'm seeing a patient

228
00:09:57.690 --> 00:10:00.270
that's older and doesn't have a history of mood disturbance,

229
00:10:00.270 --> 00:10:02.670
I'm taking a serious look across the spectrum.

230
00:10:02.670 --> 00:10:04.290
I'm looking at medications.

231
00:10:04.290 --> 00:10:07.920
By far, the most common medication for mania is steroids.

232
00:10:07.920 --> 00:10:09.270
40 milligrams of prednisone.

233
00:10:09.270 --> 00:10:12.180
Anything over 40 milligrams of prednisone increases the risk

234
00:10:12.180 --> 00:10:13.830
of neuropsychiatric side effects,

235
00:10:13.830 --> 00:10:15.813
in a very dose dependent manner.

236
00:10:17.460 --> 00:10:20.430
So you see very high doses, you can see mania with steroids.

237
00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:23.040
Drugs of abuse are usually the stimulant type.

238
00:10:23.040 --> 00:10:26.580
Neurological disorders, probably one of the more common ones

239
00:10:26.580 --> 00:10:27.810
are temporal lobe epilepsy.

240
00:10:27.810 --> 00:10:29.820
Epilepsy can present with mania.

241
00:10:29.820 --> 00:10:32.550
Endocrine disorders, hyperthyroidism is

242
00:10:32.550 --> 00:10:34.260
kind of the no-brainer, but interestingly,

243
00:10:34.260 --> 00:10:36.690
also hypothyroidism has been linked

244
00:10:36.690 --> 00:10:40.050
to mania, bipolar disorder.

245
00:10:40.050 --> 00:10:42.690
Infectious diseases, kind of the prototypical one

246
00:10:42.690 --> 00:10:46.560
is herpes encephalitis, has that change in personality

247
00:10:46.560 --> 00:10:48.300
that often comes across as very manic.

248
00:10:48.300 --> 00:10:50.013
And then autoimmune diseases,

249
00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.250
probably the real cool autoimmune disease right now

250
00:10:53.250 --> 00:10:55.380
is autoimmune encephalitis.

251
00:10:55.380 --> 00:10:57.990
Have any of you read the book, "My Brain on Fire"

252
00:10:57.990 --> 00:10:58.823
and stuff like that?

253
00:10:58.823 --> 00:11:00.543
Yeah, really cool book,

254
00:11:01.650 --> 00:11:04.290
so I encourage people to take a look at that.

255
00:11:04.290 --> 00:11:07.980
It's a biological presenting very psychiatrically.

256
00:11:07.980 --> 00:11:10.890
All right, so another question here,

257
00:11:10.890 --> 00:11:13.170
which is true about the treatment of bipolar disorder:

258
00:11:13.170 --> 00:11:15.600
valproate is effective for both acute mania

259
00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:18.780
and patients who have rapid cycles;

260
00:11:18.780 --> 00:11:21.600
women with bipolar disorder can continue valproate

261
00:11:21.600 --> 00:11:24.600
if they become pregnant, and it's been effective;

262
00:11:24.600 --> 00:11:27.810
lithium has not demonstrated an impact on suicide risk

263
00:11:27.810 --> 00:11:29.040
in bipolar disorder;

264
00:11:29.040 --> 00:11:31.533
and lithium is hepatically metabolized?

265
00:11:37.230 --> 00:11:38.670
All right, really good.

266
00:11:38.670 --> 00:11:41.550
So A is the right answer, and I'm glad I'm given the talk

267
00:11:41.550 --> 00:11:44.760
because 39 people answering B is too many,

268
00:11:44.760 --> 00:11:46.920
so we're gonna talk about that,

269
00:11:46.920 --> 00:11:48.540
in regards to valproate and pregnancy,

270
00:11:48.540 --> 00:11:50.220
and even valproate in the context

271
00:11:50.220 --> 00:11:51.813
of women of childbearing age.

272
00:11:52.860 --> 00:11:54.930
So goal of the treatment of bipolar is, one,

273
00:11:54.930 --> 00:11:57.540
to do that assessment to look for a differential diagnosis

274
00:11:57.540 --> 00:11:58.590
and address those.

275
00:11:58.590 --> 00:12:01.860
Number two is really taking,

276
00:12:01.860 --> 00:12:04.230
addressing the mood-destabilizing property.

277
00:12:04.230 --> 00:12:06.750
If somebody's manic, I wanna treat their mania

278
00:12:06.750 --> 00:12:09.120
without making them depressed in overshooting

279
00:12:09.120 --> 00:12:10.140
and making them depressed.

280
00:12:10.140 --> 00:12:10.980
If somebody's depressed,

281
00:12:10.980 --> 00:12:12.630
I don't wanna overshoot and make them manic,

282
00:12:12.630 --> 00:12:15.450
and if somebody's in a maintenance phase and euthymic,

283
00:12:15.450 --> 00:12:18.900
I don't wanna cause an exacerbation in either direction,

284
00:12:18.900 --> 00:12:20.133
so we'll address that.

285
00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:23.220
So these are the medications that have been approved

286
00:12:23.220 --> 00:12:25.170
for the various states by the FDA.

287
00:12:25.170 --> 00:12:27.150
And you can kind of see we have more for hypomania,

288
00:12:27.150 --> 00:12:30.900
quite little for depression in the context of bipolar,

289
00:12:30.900 --> 00:12:32.130
and some for maintenance,

290
00:12:32.130 --> 00:12:34.830
but what's disappointing is I only found two

291
00:12:34.830 --> 00:12:37.680
that go across all three of those, okay?

292
00:12:37.680 --> 00:12:39.810
You have Olanzapine, which I don't tend to use

293
00:12:39.810 --> 00:12:41.460
because of its metabolic sequelae,

294
00:12:41.460 --> 00:12:42.450
and you have quetiapine,

295
00:12:42.450 --> 00:12:45.360
which I'm a little bit more comfortable with using,

296
00:12:45.360 --> 00:12:46.650
much more comfortable with using

297
00:12:46.650 --> 00:12:47.820
in these patient populations.

298
00:12:47.820 --> 00:12:50.670
But we do know lithium is effective for depression.

299
00:12:50.670 --> 00:12:52.590
It's got an FDA approval for maintenance,

300
00:12:52.590 --> 00:12:54.450
and we think valproate is also effective

301
00:12:54.450 --> 00:12:56.160
for depression and maintenance,

302
00:12:56.160 --> 00:12:58.113
so we have that available as well.

303
00:12:59.820 --> 00:13:01.830
Sometimes we have to think about the patient's

304
00:13:01.830 --> 00:13:03.300
underlying medical illnesses

305
00:13:03.300 --> 00:13:05.370
to allow us to pick a medication.

306
00:13:05.370 --> 00:13:08.010
So I tend to avoid lithium in renal disease.

307
00:13:08.010 --> 00:13:10.200
I tend to think twice about giving valproate

308
00:13:10.200 --> 00:13:12.090
in somebody with bad liver disease.

309
00:13:12.090 --> 00:13:15.090
If they're already obese or on the threshold of diabetes,

310
00:13:15.090 --> 00:13:18.450
I tend to stay very clear of olanzapine.

311
00:13:18.450 --> 00:13:21.870
If they have a tendency to extrapyramidal side effects,

312
00:13:21.870 --> 00:13:24.690
I won't use aripiprazole or Risperdal.

313
00:13:24.690 --> 00:13:26.160
And women of childbearing age,

314
00:13:26.160 --> 00:13:27.300
whether they're pregnant or not,

315
00:13:27.300 --> 00:13:29.760
I won't use valproate,

316
00:13:29.760 --> 00:13:32.730
unless they're on a fairly permanent birth control,

317
00:13:32.730 --> 00:13:34.170
then it's a consideration.

318
00:13:34.170 --> 00:13:36.180
And if somebody has bipolar disorder,

319
00:13:36.180 --> 00:13:39.480
I don't use unopposed antidepressants, if at all possible.

320
00:13:39.480 --> 00:13:41.370
I'll use an antidepressant potentially,

321
00:13:41.370 --> 00:13:44.043
but they're on another mood stabilizer, okay?

322
00:13:45.210 --> 00:13:47.760
So lithium, we'll go through each of these.

323
00:13:47.760 --> 00:13:50.130
Benefits, it's probably got the best history

324
00:13:50.130 --> 00:13:52.020
for the treatment of bipolar disorder.

325
00:13:52.020 --> 00:13:54.183
It reduces risk of mania and depression.

326
00:13:56.430 --> 00:13:58.620
It's the only bipolar medication that's been shown

327
00:13:58.620 --> 00:14:02.250
to reduce suicide in patients with bipolar disorder.

328
00:14:02.250 --> 00:14:04.320
What's nice is it's not hepatically metabolized,

329
00:14:04.320 --> 00:14:06.720
so I don't have to worry about all those P450 interactions.

330
00:14:06.720 --> 00:14:08.640
Unfortunately, it's only renally excreted,

331
00:14:08.640 --> 00:14:11.190
so I have to worry about lots of medications

332
00:14:11.190 --> 00:14:12.900
that may impair its renal excretion,

333
00:14:12.900 --> 00:14:14.370
and we'll talk about that in the next slide.

334
00:14:14.370 --> 00:14:17.760
And it has a very narrow therapeutic index.

335
00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:20.610
These are some of the more common side effects.

336
00:14:20.610 --> 00:14:22.770
The biggest one is experiences tremor,

337
00:14:22.770 --> 00:14:25.560
but we have to follow longitudinally

338
00:14:25.560 --> 00:14:26.760
their thyroid condition,

339
00:14:26.760 --> 00:14:29.340
as well as a BMP looking for kidney disease

340
00:14:29.340 --> 00:14:30.690
as we're following that.

341
00:14:30.690 --> 00:14:32.520
As people have been on it, it's usually once

342
00:14:32.520 --> 00:14:35.550
or twice a year we'll check these levels going forward.

343
00:14:35.550 --> 00:14:37.320
Psychiatrists are usually pretty good.

344
00:14:37.320 --> 00:14:39.660
It's been drilled into them to check these,

345
00:14:39.660 --> 00:14:41.580
but it's always good, as a primary care provider,

346
00:14:41.580 --> 00:14:43.590
that if they're on these

347
00:14:43.590 --> 00:14:45.960
and you have a shared medical record with the psychiatrist,

348
00:14:45.960 --> 00:14:47.823
that these are documented.

349
00:14:48.660 --> 00:14:52.263
It has a narrow therapeutic index, 0.6 to 1.2,

350
00:14:53.970 --> 00:14:56.730
and even a little above that 1.2,

351
00:14:56.730 --> 00:14:59.070
you start getting nausea and tremor,

352
00:14:59.070 --> 00:15:01.890
impaired renal function, and impaired renal function

353
00:15:01.890 --> 00:15:06.090
impairs the excretion of lithium even more quite rapidly.

354
00:15:06.090 --> 00:15:07.290
Unless you change the dose,

355
00:15:07.290 --> 00:15:10.140
you can develop pretty significant toxicity

356
00:15:10.140 --> 00:15:12.750
that can lead to delirium, coma, and death.

357
00:15:12.750 --> 00:15:15.030
So we tend to be very careful

358
00:15:15.030 --> 00:15:17.910
about co-administering different medications.

359
00:15:17.910 --> 00:15:20.100
Chronic NSAIDs can impair the excretion.

360
00:15:20.100 --> 00:15:24.450
I will tell you, the addition of a thiazide diuretic

361
00:15:24.450 --> 00:15:27.060
to lithium will double the level.

362
00:15:27.060 --> 00:15:29.940
That's where I've seen the most issues with toxicity.

363
00:15:29.940 --> 00:15:31.770
One of the individuals that came up to talk to me

364
00:15:31.770 --> 00:15:34.590
was talking about the importance of shared medical records.

365
00:15:34.590 --> 00:15:36.180
I really think that that speaks

366
00:15:36.180 --> 00:15:38.160
to the importance of shared medical records.

367
00:15:38.160 --> 00:15:40.350
You would need to know that the patient's on lithium,

368
00:15:40.350 --> 00:15:41.610
the psychiatrist needs to know

369
00:15:41.610 --> 00:15:44.190
the patient may be on hydrochlorothiazide

370
00:15:44.190 --> 00:15:45.393
kind of going forward.

371
00:15:46.800 --> 00:15:49.440
ACE inhibitors have been noted to increase lithium levels,

372
00:15:49.440 --> 00:15:51.090
but usually in patients who already have

373
00:15:51.090 --> 00:15:53.010
decreased renal function or are dehydrated.

374
00:15:53.010 --> 00:15:54.870
I consider that fairly safe.

375
00:15:54.870 --> 00:15:57.170
And then thyroid function, we have to monitor.

376
00:15:58.560 --> 00:16:00.840
Valproate, its benefit has to do,

377
00:16:00.840 --> 00:16:03.150
it works for mania and depression, like lithium.

378
00:16:03.150 --> 00:16:05.790
It's safer to use, from a therapeutic index.

379
00:16:05.790 --> 00:16:08.160
We'll talk a little bit about that.

380
00:16:08.160 --> 00:16:10.680
And it seems to be superior to lithium, at least,

381
00:16:10.680 --> 00:16:12.450
for patients with that rapid, cycling,

382
00:16:12.450 --> 00:16:14.220
irritable type of bipolar disorder.

383
00:16:14.220 --> 00:16:16.110
That's why it was the right answer.

384
00:16:16.110 --> 00:16:19.710
The risks are teratogenicity,

385
00:16:19.710 --> 00:16:21.960
physical and kind of behavioral,

386
00:16:21.960 --> 00:16:23.790
and we'll talk a little bit about that.

387
00:16:23.790 --> 00:16:26.610
It's also an issue for just women of childbearing

388
00:16:26.610 --> 00:16:29.190
because of polycystic ovarian disease is really common

389
00:16:29.190 --> 00:16:32.070
in patients on chronic valproate as well,

390
00:16:32.070 --> 00:16:35.520
so we like to really avoid it in that patient population.

391
00:16:35.520 --> 00:16:37.650
Its levels are 60 to 120.

392
00:16:37.650 --> 00:16:39.750
You check a level within four days

393
00:16:39.750 --> 00:16:41.223
before their morning dose.

394
00:16:42.570 --> 00:16:44.940
I will tell you, for those of you that are following these,

395
00:16:44.940 --> 00:16:46.860
whether it's for epilepsy or bipolar,

396
00:16:46.860 --> 00:16:48.540
if you have an elderly patient

397
00:16:48.540 --> 00:16:50.970
who may be a little cachectic or malnourished,

398
00:16:50.970 --> 00:16:52.560
don't check the total levels.

399
00:16:52.560 --> 00:16:53.610
Check the free levels

400
00:16:53.610 --> 00:16:55.800
that take the protein out of the picture.

401
00:16:55.800 --> 00:16:58.440
That'll give you a more accurate representation

402
00:16:58.440 --> 00:16:59.640
of their risk of toxicity,

403
00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:01.443
and that range is six to 12.

404
00:17:02.310 --> 00:17:05.010
Depakote can impact platelets and WBC,

405
00:17:05.010 --> 00:17:06.930
so we check CBCs intermittently,

406
00:17:06.930 --> 00:17:09.060
as well as liver function tests.

407
00:17:09.060 --> 00:17:11.700
Of note here, this hyper ammonia state,

408
00:17:11.700 --> 00:17:14.883
unlike with patients with alcoholic liver disease,

409
00:17:16.435 --> 00:17:18.780
patients on valproate don't need liver impairment

410
00:17:18.780 --> 00:17:20.280
to get elevated ammonias.

411
00:17:20.280 --> 00:17:22.680
So if you have somebody who's coming in more confused,

412
00:17:22.680 --> 00:17:26.880
lethargic, you check their level, their level's fine,

413
00:17:26.880 --> 00:17:28.560
check an ammonia level.

414
00:17:28.560 --> 00:17:29.913
Look to see if that's high.

415
00:17:31.230 --> 00:17:33.960
Atypical antipsychotics in bipolar disorder

416
00:17:33.960 --> 00:17:36.030
are becoming more and more commonly used

417
00:17:36.030 --> 00:17:37.800
because they're easier to use.

418
00:17:37.800 --> 00:17:39.870
I don't have to monitor blood levels.

419
00:17:39.870 --> 00:17:41.520
I can titrate them faster.

420
00:17:41.520 --> 00:17:43.950
I can actually initiate some at a therapeutic dose.

421
00:17:43.950 --> 00:17:46.350
I don't have to taper or titrate anything.

422
00:17:46.350 --> 00:17:47.670
They're easier to use in patients

423
00:17:47.670 --> 00:17:50.310
that may have renal and hepatic function.

424
00:17:50.310 --> 00:17:51.450
I just take that into account

425
00:17:51.450 --> 00:17:53.760
as I'm initiating dose and titrating,

426
00:17:53.760 --> 00:17:57.030
and commonly they're used in conjunction

427
00:17:57.030 --> 00:17:59.160
with a more typical mood stabilizer

428
00:17:59.160 --> 00:18:02.070
like lithium or like valproate.

429
00:18:02.070 --> 00:18:04.560
The risks are primarily those of an antipsychotic.

430
00:18:04.560 --> 00:18:06.420
They're extrapyramidal symptoms.

431
00:18:06.420 --> 00:18:07.890
Olanzapine and quetiapine

432
00:18:07.890 --> 00:18:09.990
have pretty significant metabolic sequelae,

433
00:18:09.990 --> 00:18:13.620
olanzapine, logarithmically, more than quetiapine,

434
00:18:13.620 --> 00:18:16.230
but it's still an issue and does require blood work

435
00:18:16.230 --> 00:18:18.720
when you're prescribing atypical antipsychotics

436
00:18:18.720 --> 00:18:20.160
to monitor for their glucose,

437
00:18:20.160 --> 00:18:23.490
to monitor their HDL and LDL kind of going forward.

438
00:18:23.490 --> 00:18:26.550
And then as we just heard with the speaker before me,

439
00:18:26.550 --> 00:18:29.640
the QT prolongation concerns with these medications

440
00:18:29.640 --> 00:18:32.790
are a real thing that we have to take into account.

441
00:18:32.790 --> 00:18:35.070
So switching gears from bipolar disorder

442
00:18:35.070 --> 00:18:37.380
and the treatment to anxiety disorders,

443
00:18:37.380 --> 00:18:40.950
we're gonna focus on four, primarily panic-specific phobia,

444
00:18:40.950 --> 00:18:43.590
social as well as generalized anxiety disorder,

445
00:18:43.590 --> 00:18:46.020
but we're gonna start out with a question here.

446
00:18:46.020 --> 00:18:48.120
We have a young woman who presents

447
00:18:48.120 --> 00:18:51.150
with three to four panic attacks every week.

448
00:18:51.150 --> 00:18:54.300
With that, deciding that she has a panic disorder,

449
00:18:54.300 --> 00:18:57.480
which would be your pharmacotherapy of choice:

450
00:18:57.480 --> 00:19:00.780
as needed quetiapine; scheduled buspirone;

451
00:19:00.780 --> 00:19:03.360
as needed alprazolam, a benzodiazepine;

452
00:19:03.360 --> 00:19:04.743
or scheduled sertraline?

453
00:19:10.050 --> 00:19:11.820
Yeah, the answer here,

454
00:19:11.820 --> 00:19:13.050
and it's what you guys are getting,

455
00:19:13.050 --> 00:19:17.160
are the scheduled sertraline, I'm very glad.

456
00:19:17.160 --> 00:19:20.100
As needed alprazolam is a little bit lower,

457
00:19:20.100 --> 00:19:22.590
but we'll talk about why that could be.

458
00:19:22.590 --> 00:19:25.530
So anxiety disorders are amazingly common.

459
00:19:25.530 --> 00:19:29.310
About 18% of individuals are affected in any given year,

460
00:19:29.310 --> 00:19:32.940
and about 25%, about 30%, rather,

461
00:19:32.940 --> 00:19:33.990
over the course of their lives

462
00:19:33.990 --> 00:19:35.913
will suffer from an anxiety disorder.

463
00:19:36.900 --> 00:19:39.090
Patients, very much like depressed patients,

464
00:19:39.090 --> 00:19:41.460
don't often present with, "I'm sad and unhedonic."

465
00:19:41.460 --> 00:19:42.870
They present with somatic complaints.

466
00:19:42.870 --> 00:19:45.060
That's even more true for anxiety disorders.

467
00:19:45.060 --> 00:19:48.090
With over 90% of patients with anxiety disorders,

468
00:19:48.090 --> 00:19:50.820
not coming to you saying, "I'm anxious or fearful,"

469
00:19:50.820 --> 00:19:51.817
they're coming to you saying,

470
00:19:51.817 --> 00:19:53.880
"I feel like I have palpitations.

471
00:19:53.880 --> 00:19:56.460
I feel like my heart is racing, or I'm short of breath."

472
00:19:56.460 --> 00:19:59.070
So they're coming to see us in primary care,

473
00:19:59.070 --> 00:20:01.320
not our colleagues in behavioral health often,

474
00:20:01.320 --> 00:20:04.020
so it's important that we're making these diagnoses.

475
00:20:04.020 --> 00:20:06.540
And three of the four diagnoses we're gonna cover,

476
00:20:06.540 --> 00:20:08.490
are pretty common in primary care,

477
00:20:08.490 --> 00:20:10.860
based on this Wayne Katon study.

478
00:20:10.860 --> 00:20:12.780
Between six and 8% of patients

479
00:20:12.780 --> 00:20:16.440
will have either generalized anxiety disorder or social.

480
00:20:16.440 --> 00:20:18.360
So we talked a little bit about the PHQ-9.

481
00:20:18.360 --> 00:20:20.880
How many are using the GAD-2 and GAD-7

482
00:20:20.880 --> 00:20:22.860
in your clinical practices?

483
00:20:22.860 --> 00:20:23.693
That's great.

484
00:20:23.693 --> 00:20:26.550
I'm actually waiting for the USPF services task force

485
00:20:26.550 --> 00:20:28.380
to come up with this recommendation.

486
00:20:28.380 --> 00:20:29.220
There's a GAD-2.

487
00:20:29.220 --> 00:20:32.130
You ask these two questions to screen for anxiety disorders,

488
00:20:32.130 --> 00:20:35.160
and if it's positive, we move to the GAD-7.

489
00:20:35.160 --> 00:20:37.983
Same cutoff level of 10 or more,

490
00:20:39.210 --> 00:20:42.900
with pretty so-so sensitivity and specificity.

491
00:20:42.900 --> 00:20:45.420
The important thing to realize is the GAD-7 was designed

492
00:20:45.420 --> 00:20:49.020
to study generalized anxiety disorder by itself,

493
00:20:49.020 --> 00:20:52.410
so you see a little dilution of its sensitivity

494
00:20:52.410 --> 00:20:54.780
because we're kind of looking at other disorders

495
00:20:54.780 --> 00:20:55.680
with it now.

496
00:20:55.680 --> 00:20:57.480
But it really is the standard for screening

497
00:20:57.480 --> 00:21:01.650
for anxiety disorders in primary care across populations.

498
00:21:01.650 --> 00:21:04.200
But it does have sensitivity and specificity data

499
00:21:04.200 --> 00:21:06.510
for the others, if you're interested in it.

500
00:21:06.510 --> 00:21:08.400
So what is a panic attack?

501
00:21:08.400 --> 00:21:12.060
A panic attack is a discreet period

502
00:21:12.060 --> 00:21:14.730
of intense fear or anxiety

503
00:21:14.730 --> 00:21:16.680
that kind of comes out of the blue,

504
00:21:16.680 --> 00:21:19.110
tends to peak after about 10 minutes,

505
00:21:19.110 --> 00:21:21.060
and then gradually kind of dissipates.

506
00:21:21.060 --> 00:21:22.740
It can be triggered by a stimulus,

507
00:21:22.740 --> 00:21:24.900
but it can also come out of the blue.

508
00:21:24.900 --> 00:21:27.210
Some people actually wake up with panic disorders,

509
00:21:27.210 --> 00:21:29.220
straight out of their sleep and have it.

510
00:21:29.220 --> 00:21:31.980
In addition, how that anxiety comes through

511
00:21:31.980 --> 00:21:33.330
is at least four symptoms,

512
00:21:33.330 --> 00:21:35.820
primarily surrounding autonomic arousal.

513
00:21:35.820 --> 00:21:38.730
It's tachycardia, it's palpitations, it's chest pain,

514
00:21:38.730 --> 00:21:41.310
it's shortness of breath, it's GI distress,

515
00:21:41.310 --> 00:21:44.310
it's nausea, it's feelings of paresthesia.

516
00:21:44.310 --> 00:21:46.710
It's psychological symptoms of, "I'm dying."

517
00:21:46.710 --> 00:21:48.637
It's impending doom or derealization.

518
00:21:48.637 --> 00:21:50.670
"I feel like I'm outside of my body."

519
00:21:50.670 --> 00:21:53.040
It's some cluster of four of those symptoms.

520
00:21:53.040 --> 00:21:55.830
And panic attacks can really happen in any disorder,

521
00:21:55.830 --> 00:21:58.770
depression, generalized anxiety disorder,

522
00:21:58.770 --> 00:22:01.560
but they can also happen in panic disorder,

523
00:22:01.560 --> 00:22:04.833
and panic disorder is when you have panic attacks,

524
00:22:05.760 --> 00:22:07.710
but these panic attacks are followed

525
00:22:07.710 --> 00:22:10.560
by at least one month of, you know, concern

526
00:22:10.560 --> 00:22:11.767
about what these attacks mean.

527
00:22:11.767 --> 00:22:14.820
"Am I having a stroke? Am I having a heart attack?"

528
00:22:14.820 --> 00:22:18.690
There's concern about having another episode in the future.

529
00:22:18.690 --> 00:22:21.270
And sometimes the concern about having another episode

530
00:22:21.270 --> 00:22:24.877
in the future leads individuals to change their lifestyle.

531
00:22:24.877 --> 00:22:27.570
"I've had three panic attacks at the grocery store.

532
00:22:27.570 --> 00:22:30.780
I am not going to that grocery store anymore," okay?

533
00:22:30.780 --> 00:22:32.700
That's a change in their type of behavior,

534
00:22:32.700 --> 00:22:34.710
and those three issues are required

535
00:22:34.710 --> 00:22:37.500
for the diagnosis of a panic disorder.

536
00:22:37.500 --> 00:22:40.500
It's actually fairly common, 1.5 to 3.5.

537
00:22:40.500 --> 00:22:42.660
Much more common, two to three times more common

538
00:22:42.660 --> 00:22:44.280
in women than in men.

539
00:22:44.280 --> 00:22:46.860
And it's often quite a chronic disease.

540
00:22:46.860 --> 00:22:49.200
It may get worse in periods of stress.

541
00:22:49.200 --> 00:22:52.770
Take-home point is over 90% have a psychiatric comorbidity.

542
00:22:52.770 --> 00:22:54.720
Most of those psychiatric comorbidities

543
00:22:54.720 --> 00:22:56.640
are other anxiety disorders,

544
00:22:56.640 --> 00:22:59.970
but a good 10 to 30% have major depressive disorder.

545
00:22:59.970 --> 00:23:03.540
And the good news is that pharmacotherapy are SSRIs,

546
00:23:03.540 --> 00:23:06.060
or SNRIs, two birds, one stone,

547
00:23:06.060 --> 00:23:08.610
the depression and the anxiety.

548
00:23:08.610 --> 00:23:10.170
And then cognitive behavioral therapy.

549
00:23:10.170 --> 00:23:12.030
Again, that's usually the answer on the test.

550
00:23:12.030 --> 00:23:14.250
If somebody's asking about a therapy question,

551
00:23:14.250 --> 00:23:16.080
it's appropriate for these disorders

552
00:23:16.080 --> 00:23:18.150
just like it is for depression.

553
00:23:18.150 --> 00:23:20.520
Now, generalized anxiety disorder is what my wife,

554
00:23:20.520 --> 00:23:22.770
who is a psychiatrist, says I got

555
00:23:22.770 --> 00:23:25.050
when my daughter started dating.

556
00:23:25.050 --> 00:23:27.480
That affect you have when you hear

557
00:23:27.480 --> 00:23:30.180
that my children have both parents as psychiatrist,

558
00:23:30.180 --> 00:23:35.160
that's pity, so that's what my kids often remind us of here.

559
00:23:35.160 --> 00:23:38.670
So why she thought I had this is I had excessive anxiety

560
00:23:38.670 --> 00:23:40.380
and worry, according to her, more days than not,

561
00:23:40.380 --> 00:23:43.030
for at least the first six months of her dating life.

562
00:23:44.130 --> 00:23:46.110
Surrounding that, I actually corrected her,

563
00:23:46.110 --> 00:23:47.880
it's only about the dating,

564
00:23:47.880 --> 00:23:51.720
so it actually fails the criteria based on multiple events,

565
00:23:51.720 --> 00:23:55.920
but I definitely did have these three or more symptoms.

566
00:23:55.920 --> 00:23:58.350
I had the restlessness, I wasn't sleeping,

567
00:23:58.350 --> 00:24:00.570
I was tense, every one of her boyfriends

568
00:24:00.570 --> 00:24:03.510
could have sensed my irritability, and all of that.

569
00:24:03.510 --> 00:24:05.940
So we are actually able to get this.

570
00:24:05.940 --> 00:24:08.820
It's quite a common condition, as I allude to.

571
00:24:08.820 --> 00:24:10.050
I don't mean to minimize it.

572
00:24:10.050 --> 00:24:13.650
So it's chronic, over six months, over multiple events,

573
00:24:13.650 --> 00:24:16.560
and they have at least three of the following symptoms.

574
00:24:16.560 --> 00:24:18.300
It's actually more common than panic disorder,

575
00:24:18.300 --> 00:24:20.280
and about 5%, two to one ratio.

576
00:24:20.280 --> 00:24:23.580
Similar to panic disorder, more women than men.

577
00:24:23.580 --> 00:24:26.040
Its age of onset is commonly in childhood.

578
00:24:26.040 --> 00:24:27.690
If you ask adults who have this

579
00:24:27.690 --> 00:24:29.220
about their anxiety in childhood,

580
00:24:29.220 --> 00:24:31.260
they'll describe themselves as worriers,

581
00:24:31.260 --> 00:24:34.410
worry warts, other things like that as they were growing up.

582
00:24:34.410 --> 00:24:37.650
It's chronic, but fluctuates at periods of stress,

583
00:24:37.650 --> 00:24:39.960
i.e. daughter dating.

584
00:24:39.960 --> 00:24:43.650
And then it's the treatment again, trend.

585
00:24:43.650 --> 00:24:47.580
You notice a trend here, SSRIs, SNRIs, and CBT.

586
00:24:47.580 --> 00:24:48.750
It's not uncommon for people

587
00:24:48.750 --> 00:24:52.533
with generalized anxiety disorder to have panic disorder.

588
00:24:53.580 --> 00:24:56.490
Social phobia is when there's fear or anxiety

589
00:24:56.490 --> 00:24:59.430
that surround being in a situation

590
00:24:59.430 --> 00:25:01.890
that's where you can be criticized by others.

591
00:25:01.890 --> 00:25:05.760
This can be a party, this could be giving a talk

592
00:25:05.760 --> 00:25:07.410
in front of others, okay?

593
00:25:07.410 --> 00:25:09.810
That's typically called performance anxiety.

594
00:25:09.810 --> 00:25:13.140
And those situations provoke intense anxiety

595
00:25:13.140 --> 00:25:16.053
every time you're in those situations, okay?

596
00:25:17.250 --> 00:25:18.420
It's actually more common

597
00:25:18.420 --> 00:25:19.560
than the other ones we talked about,

598
00:25:19.560 --> 00:25:22.980
with up to about 10 to 13% of patients developing it.

599
00:25:22.980 --> 00:25:25.380
It has an onset in adolescence.

600
00:25:25.380 --> 00:25:29.130
More common across the population in females,

601
00:25:29.130 --> 00:25:32.400
but in specialty centers, for whatever reason,

602
00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:34.980
when you talk about it, seems to be more common in males,

603
00:25:34.980 --> 00:25:36.420
in at least the treatment settings.

604
00:25:36.420 --> 00:25:38.940
And very common comorbidity is depression

605
00:25:38.940 --> 00:25:40.200
and actually substance uses.

606
00:25:40.200 --> 00:25:42.270
People with chronic social phobia

607
00:25:42.270 --> 00:25:45.510
tend to try to address that with alcohol sometimes.

608
00:25:45.510 --> 00:25:48.330
The pharmacotherapy is, if it's really chronic,

609
00:25:48.330 --> 00:25:51.030
generalized kind of social phobia about any situation,

610
00:25:51.030 --> 00:25:52.920
we tend to schedule SSRIs.

611
00:25:52.920 --> 00:25:56.250
If it's performance related, we can use PRN benzodiazepines

612
00:25:56.250 --> 00:25:58.275
or PRN propanolol.

613
00:25:58.275 --> 00:26:01.860
And again, cognitive behavioral therapy is often optimal.

614
00:26:01.860 --> 00:26:04.410
Specific phobia is that intense fear

615
00:26:04.410 --> 00:26:07.140
about a specific situation or object,

616
00:26:07.140 --> 00:26:10.800
i.e., heights, spiders, snakes, those kind of things.

617
00:26:10.800 --> 00:26:12.780
When confronted with the object,

618
00:26:12.780 --> 00:26:16.920
almost invariably, you have a resulting panic attack

619
00:26:16.920 --> 00:26:18.810
or intense anxiety or fear.

620
00:26:18.810 --> 00:26:21.420
Think Indiana Jones in that pit of spiders,

621
00:26:21.420 --> 00:26:22.740
that kind of stuff.

622
00:26:22.740 --> 00:26:25.410
Lifetime prevalence is about 10%.

623
00:26:25.410 --> 00:26:26.640
And interestingly enough,

624
00:26:26.640 --> 00:26:29.790
fears tend to change from younger age to older age.

625
00:26:29.790 --> 00:26:33.240
The most common fear in an elderly individual,

626
00:26:33.240 --> 00:26:34.830
you guys know what that is?

627
00:26:34.830 --> 00:26:38.052
It's actually falling, all right?

628
00:26:38.052 --> 00:26:39.510
It doesn't have a specific phobia name,

629
00:26:39.510 --> 00:26:42.420
but in screening patients about their fears in elderly,

630
00:26:42.420 --> 00:26:43.950
it's often falling.

631
00:26:43.950 --> 00:26:47.130
The pharmacotherapy, not in elderly patients

632
00:26:47.130 --> 00:26:49.743
with the fear of falling, are PRN benzodiazepines,

633
00:26:51.180 --> 00:26:52.740
if it's kind of an infrequent thing,

634
00:26:52.740 --> 00:26:55.050
such as flying or things like that,

635
00:26:55.050 --> 00:26:56.820
but the best treatment is, again,

636
00:26:56.820 --> 00:26:58.260
that cognitive behavioral therapy,

637
00:26:58.260 --> 00:26:59.820
getting to the root of the concern

638
00:26:59.820 --> 00:27:02.880
and correcting those cognitive misinterpretations.

639
00:27:02.880 --> 00:27:05.400
Again, my trend of anxiety as a symptom,

640
00:27:05.400 --> 00:27:06.930
what could be causing it?

641
00:27:06.930 --> 00:27:10.800
We have these very physiological things such as hypoxia.

642
00:27:10.800 --> 00:27:13.170
Medications, a common medication, actually,

643
00:27:13.170 --> 00:27:16.170
can be antidepressants that are started too rapidly

644
00:27:16.170 --> 00:27:18.900
in patients with anxiety, will make anxiety worse.

645
00:27:18.900 --> 00:27:20.673
And then dopamine antagonists,

646
00:27:22.592 --> 00:27:25.800
the Thorazine we use for nausea,

647
00:27:25.800 --> 00:27:28.920
the Haldol we use for antipsychotics,

648
00:27:28.920 --> 00:27:31.170
those cause a side effect called akathisia,

649
00:27:31.170 --> 00:27:33.123
that often mimics anxiety.

650
00:27:33.990 --> 00:27:38.280
All right, in randomly controlled trials,

651
00:27:38.280 --> 00:27:41.130
drug versus placebo, which of the following treatments

652
00:27:41.130 --> 00:27:43.800
fail to demonstrate any efficacy or benefit

653
00:27:43.800 --> 00:27:46.740
in the treatment of GAD, generalized anxiety disorder:

654
00:27:46.740 --> 00:27:49.710
antidepressants, benzodiazepines, beta blockers,

655
00:27:49.710 --> 00:27:51.093
or cognitive therapy?

656
00:27:56.289 --> 00:27:58.170
All right, 50/50. This is good.

657
00:27:58.170 --> 00:27:59.280
I like this.

658
00:27:59.280 --> 00:28:01.440
All right, so let's talk a little bit about this.

659
00:28:01.440 --> 00:28:05.220
So the SSRIs and the SNRIs are the first line treatments

660
00:28:05.220 --> 00:28:07.950
for all of those anxiety disorders we've talked about,

661
00:28:07.950 --> 00:28:09.660
panic disorder and other anxiety disorders.

662
00:28:09.660 --> 00:28:10.493
Why?

663
00:28:10.493 --> 00:28:12.480
Because they work across those disorders,

664
00:28:12.480 --> 00:28:13.440
as well as depression,

665
00:28:13.440 --> 00:28:16.350
and comorbidity is often more the rule than the exception.

666
00:28:16.350 --> 00:28:19.530
When they work, the patient no longer experiences

667
00:28:19.530 --> 00:28:21.960
any anxiety, which is key.

668
00:28:21.960 --> 00:28:24.510
That's very different than PRN benzos, okay?

669
00:28:24.510 --> 00:28:26.130
That requires somebody to feel miserable

670
00:28:26.130 --> 00:28:27.690
before they take something.

671
00:28:27.690 --> 00:28:29.880
They're well tolerated and safe in overdose.

672
00:28:29.880 --> 00:28:33.210
I don't also have to worry about physiological tolerance,

673
00:28:33.210 --> 00:28:34.830
potential dependence developing

674
00:28:34.830 --> 00:28:37.380
with these medications like I do.

675
00:28:37.380 --> 00:28:39.690
Some of the key aspects to use them in anxiety,

676
00:28:39.690 --> 00:28:41.580
and this is really key, is start low,

677
00:28:41.580 --> 00:28:43.170
start at half of the normal dose

678
00:28:43.170 --> 00:28:45.060
you normally would for depression.

679
00:28:45.060 --> 00:28:47.010
So if you're starting Zoloft sertraline,

680
00:28:47.010 --> 00:28:48.960
start at 25 milligrams for a week,

681
00:28:48.960 --> 00:28:50.310
make sure they tolerate it.

682
00:28:50.310 --> 00:28:52.680
You wanna avoid that activation and that anxiety

683
00:28:52.680 --> 00:28:54.870
that occur with starting at too high a dose.

684
00:28:54.870 --> 00:28:57.630
If they do well at 25 in a week, you can increase it,

685
00:28:57.630 --> 00:28:59.310
and you gradually titrate the dose.

686
00:28:59.310 --> 00:29:00.990
The good news is it's the same dose

687
00:29:00.990 --> 00:29:03.060
you'd use for antidepressant,

688
00:29:03.060 --> 00:29:05.640
is the dose you'd use for an anxiety disorder.

689
00:29:05.640 --> 00:29:08.850
The bad news is it still takes four to six weeks to work.

690
00:29:08.850 --> 00:29:11.700
This is where I feel benzodiazepines play a role.

691
00:29:11.700 --> 00:29:14.190
I use long-acting scheduled benzodiazepines

692
00:29:14.190 --> 00:29:18.253
for four to six weeks to allow the SSRI

693
00:29:18.253 --> 00:29:19.440
or SNRI to work.

694
00:29:19.440 --> 00:29:21.480
And I tell the patient when I start it

695
00:29:21.480 --> 00:29:24.510
that they're coming off of it in six weeks.

696
00:29:24.510 --> 00:29:25.620
I am tapering them.

697
00:29:25.620 --> 00:29:27.540
It is not a long-term medication,

698
00:29:27.540 --> 00:29:29.610
the clonazepam I would use in this case.

699
00:29:29.610 --> 00:29:31.350
So they know when I start it,

700
00:29:31.350 --> 00:29:33.420
it is not a long-term medication,

701
00:29:33.420 --> 00:29:35.190
and that makes it a lot easier.

702
00:29:35.190 --> 00:29:38.760
Not easy, a lot easier to come off of it.

703
00:29:38.760 --> 00:29:41.220
Why? Because benzos work.

704
00:29:41.220 --> 00:29:44.280
They work really well for anxiety.

705
00:29:44.280 --> 00:29:47.280
I had a brain MRI, I tried it without a benzo,

706
00:29:47.280 --> 00:29:51.420
I lasted, I am not kidding, four seconds, okay?

707
00:29:51.420 --> 00:29:54.000
I got a Xanax. Only time I've ever took it.

708
00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:55.710
I don't know if it did anything for the anxiety,

709
00:29:55.710 --> 00:29:59.640
but that piece of wood I laid on was so comfy.

710
00:29:59.640 --> 00:30:00.750
I mean, it works.

711
00:30:00.750 --> 00:30:02.850
It works really well, okay?

712
00:30:02.850 --> 00:30:04.080
And it works quick.

713
00:30:04.080 --> 00:30:05.130
It also helps with sleep,

714
00:30:05.130 --> 00:30:07.680
which is also an issue with anxiety.

715
00:30:07.680 --> 00:30:09.180
Its risk is tolerance.

716
00:30:09.180 --> 00:30:11.550
Physical tolerance can lead to dependence.

717
00:30:11.550 --> 00:30:15.090
You end up chasing your tail with chronic benzodiazepines.

718
00:30:15.090 --> 00:30:17.700
Works for a while, need to increase the dose.

719
00:30:17.700 --> 00:30:19.980
Stops working, needs to increase the dose.

720
00:30:19.980 --> 00:30:21.720
Tolerance develops, and it can be hell

721
00:30:21.720 --> 00:30:23.250
to get these patients off benzos.

722
00:30:23.250 --> 00:30:25.230
I'm sure we've all encountered those.

723
00:30:25.230 --> 00:30:28.530
And then in the elderly, sedation, falls, memory impairment,

724
00:30:28.530 --> 00:30:30.750
there's actually some data to suggest

725
00:30:30.750 --> 00:30:32.700
that dementia may be a sequelae

726
00:30:32.700 --> 00:30:34.590
of long-term benzodiazepine prescribing,

727
00:30:34.590 --> 00:30:36.840
because if it's action on the hippocampus.

728
00:30:36.840 --> 00:30:39.210
So this may be a controversial slide,

729
00:30:39.210 --> 00:30:43.620
I really see no role for chronic benzodiazepine use

730
00:30:43.620 --> 00:30:46.200
in patients with a chronic anxiety disorder.

731
00:30:46.200 --> 00:30:49.620
Scheduled benzodiazepines may prevent the disorder,

732
00:30:49.620 --> 00:30:51.840
but they cause more harm than good in my mind.

733
00:30:51.840 --> 00:30:54.660
PRNs, unless it's very infrequent PRNs,

734
00:30:54.660 --> 00:30:56.703
once a week, couple times a month,

735
00:30:57.630 --> 00:31:00.780
and a patient can tolerate that degree of anxiety,

736
00:31:00.780 --> 00:31:02.940
that can work, but I really don't want my patients

737
00:31:02.940 --> 00:31:05.700
with frequent panic attacks to experience the panic attack.

738
00:31:05.700 --> 00:31:08.640
I wanna stop that, so that's why I use the SSRIs.

739
00:31:08.640 --> 00:31:09.600
Coming to the end here,

740
00:31:09.600 --> 00:31:12.420
other medications used for anxiety.

741
00:31:12.420 --> 00:31:14.970
Buspirone, it is only FDA approved

742
00:31:14.970 --> 00:31:17.790
for generalized anxiety disorder.

743
00:31:17.790 --> 00:31:19.560
It doesn't play a role in the treatment

744
00:31:19.560 --> 00:31:20.880
of other medications.

745
00:31:20.880 --> 00:31:21.713
The joke with buspirone,

746
00:31:21.713 --> 00:31:23.550
it is everything you want in a medication,

747
00:31:23.550 --> 00:31:25.620
i.e., no side effects, well, well tolerated,

748
00:31:25.620 --> 00:31:27.720
but it doesn't do anything.

749
00:31:27.720 --> 00:31:29.880
Only really works for generalized anxiety disorder.

750
00:31:29.880 --> 00:31:33.030
In addition, sometimes you have to dose it TID,

751
00:31:33.030 --> 00:31:33.863
which is a pain.

752
00:31:33.863 --> 00:31:36.060
Nobody ever takes a medication TID,

753
00:31:36.060 --> 00:31:37.860
and it takes a while to work.

754
00:31:37.860 --> 00:31:41.580
Hydroxyzine actually has an FDA approval for anxiety.

755
00:31:41.580 --> 00:31:43.800
It also has an FDA approval for acute disturbance

756
00:31:43.800 --> 00:31:45.933
and hysteria, which is awesome.

757
00:31:47.370 --> 00:31:50.040
We often use these as the PRN medication for anxiety

758
00:31:50.040 --> 00:31:52.710
with patients with substance abuse issues.

759
00:31:52.710 --> 00:31:54.960
It's pretty much just a sedating antihistamine.

760
00:31:54.960 --> 00:31:57.150
You dose it at 25 or 50.

761
00:31:57.150 --> 00:31:59.730
The FDA says you can dose it at 100 milligrams

762
00:31:59.730 --> 00:32:00.870
four times a day.

763
00:32:00.870 --> 00:32:03.630
I mean, they're just sleeping at that point.

764
00:32:03.630 --> 00:32:05.730
It does have some anticholinergic side effects,

765
00:32:05.730 --> 00:32:07.800
so I tend to avoid it in the elderly,

766
00:32:07.800 --> 00:32:09.540
and it's quite sedating.

767
00:32:09.540 --> 00:32:11.853
Propranolol is for performance anxiety.

768
00:32:14.220 --> 00:32:16.590
When you are concerned about cognitive impairment,

769
00:32:16.590 --> 00:32:19.410
you don't wanna dull them with a PRN benzodiazepine.

770
00:32:19.410 --> 00:32:21.450
So if I get anxious when I'm speaking,

771
00:32:21.450 --> 00:32:24.720
I would take propranolol, not a PRN Xanax,

772
00:32:24.720 --> 00:32:27.870
but it's not effective for generalized anxiety disorder.

773
00:32:27.870 --> 00:32:30.930
That's why it was the answer on the question.

774
00:32:30.930 --> 00:32:32.730
Learn this the hard way.

775
00:32:32.730 --> 00:32:34.830
I gave a patient 20 propranolol

776
00:32:34.830 --> 00:32:36.570
before they were to give a talk.

777
00:32:36.570 --> 00:32:38.250
They took it before they were to give a talk,

778
00:32:38.250 --> 00:32:40.923
stood up to give the, and fell on their face.

779
00:32:41.760 --> 00:32:44.340
So make sure that you tell the patient

780
00:32:44.340 --> 00:32:47.400
to try the dose the day before,

781
00:32:47.400 --> 00:32:50.100
and see how things go, that they don't get orthostatic

782
00:32:50.100 --> 00:32:50.933
and things like that.

783
00:32:50.933 --> 00:32:52.560
True story. I was a resident.

784
00:32:52.560 --> 00:32:53.660
It was very traumatic.

785
00:32:54.630 --> 00:32:57.570
So the key points from an anxiety and bipolar standpoint,

786
00:32:57.570 --> 00:33:00.870
bipolar I is mania, bipolar II is hypomania.

787
00:33:00.870 --> 00:33:03.330
Bipolar II can never have mania.

788
00:33:03.330 --> 00:33:05.880
Avoid antidepressants as monotherapy

789
00:33:05.880 --> 00:33:08.250
because of their risk of mood destabilization

790
00:33:08.250 --> 00:33:10.440
in both bipolar I and bipolar II.

791
00:33:10.440 --> 00:33:11.940
If you're gonna use an antidepressant,

792
00:33:11.940 --> 00:33:14.250
they should be on another mood stabilizer.

793
00:33:14.250 --> 00:33:17.640
Valproate, not a friend in childbearing.

794
00:33:17.640 --> 00:33:19.770
And then the SSRIs are considered first line

795
00:33:19.770 --> 00:33:20.850
for anxiety disorders,

796
00:33:20.850 --> 00:33:23.610
and always cognitive behavioral therapy on exam.

797
00:33:23.610 --> 00:33:26.100
All right, I'm gonna turn it over here.

798
00:33:26.100 --> 00:33:29.214
<v Announcer>Thank you very much. I appreciate it.</v>

799
00:33:29.214 --> 00:33:31.797
(bright music)

